1
00:00:01,718 --> 00:00:09,576
Namo dasa bhagavato harahato sama sambodasa.

2
00:00:10,739 --> 00:00:18,597
Namo dasa bhagavato harahato sama sambodasa.

3
00:00:19,420 --> 00:00:32,713
Namo dasa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

4
00:00:36,518 --> 00:00:38,399
I've got my little microphone as usual.

5
00:00:39,741 --> 00:00:46,609
So being spring, or April anyway, I thought we would have a go at joy.

6
00:00:47,838 --> 00:00:51,082
So the first thing I did was to look up all the synonyms we have.

7
00:00:51,481 --> 00:01:06,179
So the pleasure, enjoyment, happiness, gladness, delight, thrill, exaltation, elation, bliss, ecstasy, rapture, and absorption.

8
00:01:07,900 --> 00:01:08,742
That's not bad, is it?

9
00:01:09,522 --> 00:01:10,384
And it's all good.

10
00:01:11,063 --> 00:01:16,090
See, it's not as though the Buddha asked us to be miserable all the time, even though he...

11
00:01:16,507 --> 00:01:19,293
even though most of the teaching is about getting rid of suffering.

12
00:01:22,319 --> 00:01:27,531
You know, he was asked, how does he feel when he teaches and somebody doesn't accept the teaching?

13
00:01:27,932 --> 00:01:29,435
So he said he feels all right with it.

14
00:01:29,555 --> 00:01:30,757
It's calmer.

15
00:01:31,259 --> 00:01:36,609
But when somebody does accept his teaching, he feels happy, feels joyful.

16
00:01:40,015 --> 00:01:47,224
Now, it's an interesting thing that all my teachers never introduced us into the practice of joy.

17
00:01:47,924 --> 00:01:48,865
It's very strange.

18
00:01:49,006 --> 00:01:50,867
Metta, Metta all the time.

19
00:01:52,170 --> 00:01:55,474
Compassion a little bit, but joy never.

20
00:01:56,135 --> 00:01:58,516
And it always I don't know why.

21
00:01:58,757 --> 00:02:03,963
Well, I'm thinking that why they did it because of the problem of indulgence.

22
00:02:05,665 --> 00:02:07,888
And I think that's what goes wrong, of course.

23
00:02:08,448 --> 00:02:17,800
All these beautiful mental states to which we are heir of corrupt as soon as we try to hold on to them or want more of them.

24
00:02:19,782 --> 00:02:28,973
So it's a case of recognizing that nothing is repeatable and that when it's gone, it's gone and there's no point in anchoring after it.

25
00:02:29,442 --> 00:02:38,556
So that, for instance, if you take a morsel of food, which you delight in, you know, once you've swallowed it and you've got the aftertaste gone, that's it.

26
00:02:38,575 --> 00:02:39,096
Let go.

27
00:02:39,135 --> 00:02:47,628
Now, this fear, this fear of indulgence actually destroys joy.

28
00:02:47,669 --> 00:02:54,078
And I noticed it in the monastic life more than in lay people.

29
00:02:54,939 --> 00:02:56,461
So, for instance...

30
00:02:56,729 --> 00:03:09,513
At the monastery, Kandaboda, there would be obviously occasions when people would come with special foods to celebrate a birthday, a marriage and so on and so forth.

31
00:03:09,532 --> 00:03:16,104
And one of the things that is quite lovely is buffalo curd, miikiri.

32
00:03:16,625 --> 00:03:27,421
And it was handed out, you see, and you put loads of sugar with it, or kittle juice, a bit like maple juice, you know.

33
00:03:28,323 --> 00:03:30,225
And it's wonderful.

34
00:03:30,887 --> 00:03:32,430
And we're all eating it, you see.

35
00:03:32,509 --> 00:03:40,322
And there was a monk sat next to me who was the picture of the ascetic, you know, very gaunt, and his cheeks were like this, you know.

36
00:03:41,282 --> 00:03:42,344
And...

37
00:03:42,493 --> 00:03:43,855
And I knew him, you know.

38
00:03:43,876 --> 00:03:52,849
And as we got round, while we were eating, he was glaring, as it were, at this curd, you know.

39
00:03:53,951 --> 00:04:02,786
And as we came to the finish, he sort of leant forward quite slowly, lifted it up slowly, and then basically shoveled it down his throat.

40
00:04:04,427 --> 00:04:09,395
And I've always presumed he was just so afraid of indulgence.

41
00:04:11,467 --> 00:04:12,491
So that's no good, is it?

42
00:04:19,069 --> 00:04:20,372
There was another case, too.

43
00:04:21,435 --> 00:04:25,528
There was my teacher, Sayadaw Ujanaka.

44
00:04:25,947 --> 00:04:38,624
About, I would say around about 10 years ago, he taught at a place called Beatenberg, which is near, it's in Interlaken, which is right, you know, those beautiful lakes in Switzerland.

45
00:04:39,223 --> 00:04:46,112
And from it, on a beautiful day, you can see these three great mountains, the Eiger, the Monk and the Jungfrau.

46
00:04:46,694 --> 00:04:47,415
Anyway,

47
00:04:47,394 --> 00:04:52,100
During the retreat, the weather was miserable, rainy, cloudy, etc.

48
00:04:52,422 --> 00:04:56,466
And one day it all opened up and it's a glorious sight.

49
00:04:56,547 --> 00:05:00,192
The white peaks against this deep blue sky, you know.

50
00:05:00,211 --> 00:05:04,517
So everybody on the retreat went out onto the balcony and outside to have a look, you see.

51
00:05:04,959 --> 00:05:06,120
Well, he gave them hell, didn't he?

52
00:05:06,500 --> 00:05:07,642
He upset a lot of people.

53
00:05:07,783 --> 00:05:10,146
He told them they were useless meditators.

54
00:05:10,935 --> 00:05:14,903
They were just indulging and he's wasting his time and all sorts.

55
00:05:15,423 --> 00:05:17,728
So I don't think he was invited again.

56
00:05:19,211 --> 00:05:24,000
And I remember whenever I would say something like, you know, isn't that a beautiful flower?

57
00:05:24,461 --> 00:05:27,505
He would say, ah, yes, but it fades, you know, it fades, it dies.

58
00:05:28,208 --> 00:05:29,810
A bit of a killjoy, really.

59
00:05:30,692 --> 00:05:35,019
But his intention, of course, was to awaken me to the problem of indulgence.

60
00:05:36,485 --> 00:05:40,199
And that seed of indulgence is always there, you know, right to the bitter end.

61
00:05:41,362 --> 00:05:46,663
Mara is always right there, just waiting for the moment to creep up on us.

62
00:05:48,331 --> 00:06:02,973
So it's a case of just recognizing these two things that if we if we begin to see what the what the consequences of indulgence are, then we'll be we'll make ourselves afraid to enjoy something.

63
00:06:03,454 --> 00:06:11,146
But actually, if, for instance, you have a biscuit, right, and you finish a biscuit, the last thing goes down, flavors gone.

64
00:06:12,048 --> 00:06:12,848
And then you get this.

65
00:06:13,810 --> 00:06:14,911
I think I'll have another one.

66
00:06:15,668 --> 00:06:18,612
So as soon as that comes, you know, oh, well, that's greed.

67
00:06:18,872 --> 00:06:19,072
Right.

68
00:06:19,452 --> 00:06:23,119
So you have to sit down and wait for that to to exhaust itself.

69
00:06:23,639 --> 00:06:31,790
Now, once you've done that, you've exhausted the karmic consequence of the greed that arose while you were eating that biscuit.

70
00:06:32,512 --> 00:06:34,035
I think it's as simple as that.

71
00:06:36,237 --> 00:06:39,802
I know somebody who got into the habit of eating biscuits just before they went to bed.

72
00:06:41,521 --> 00:06:43,846
And he was getting rather afraid of it.

73
00:06:43,867 --> 00:06:46,351
So instead he turned to music.

74
00:06:46,372 --> 00:06:47,956
And now that's a skillful thing.

75
00:06:48,117 --> 00:06:57,959
If you find that, you know, an indulgence feels a little bit overwhelming, then put your attention on some other joyful thing that you like to do.

76
00:07:00,420 --> 00:07:01,242
So there we are.

77
00:07:01,302 --> 00:07:02,345
There's the fear.

78
00:07:02,704 --> 00:07:07,173
The fear of indulgence undermines, destroys enjoyment of joy.

79
00:07:07,194 --> 00:07:17,653
And to become indulgent with our joys, wanting more of this, more of the same, is just, you know, the old suffering.

80
00:07:19,404 --> 00:07:28,437
So now the question is, why is it we remember mostly at the end of the day the painful parts and hardly any of the joys, right?

81
00:07:28,456 --> 00:07:31,480
Well, I suppose the reason is because painful things hurt.

82
00:07:32,903 --> 00:07:36,247
But unfortunately, it does shadow out the joys of the day.

83
00:07:36,827 --> 00:07:40,913
So we have to make a special effort to remember the joys of the day, right?

84
00:07:40,932 --> 00:07:48,163
Instead of obsessing about our failures and our upsets, we can contemplate the successes and joys of the day.

85
00:07:48,987 --> 00:07:59,019
Now, the interesting thing is, the more you make yourself aware of the joys of the day, the more you bend that way and the more you see what is actually undermining your joy.

86
00:07:59,060 --> 00:08:02,564
And this, of course, creates even greater joy.

87
00:08:05,187 --> 00:08:12,177
So we try to rid ourselves of behaviours which undermine our joy and over time, our joy grows.

88
00:08:15,952 --> 00:08:19,920
And of course, this is done with a certain affectionate awareness.

89
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:26,651
And this is towards ourselves, you know, being kind to ourselves, gentle to ourselves and seeking what lifts the heart.

90
00:08:26,810 --> 00:08:30,958
Yeah, music, nature, friendship and so on.

91
00:08:33,571 --> 00:08:47,979
Now, this word mudita, which is one of the four Brahma-viharas, remember, so love, compassion, joy, and peacefulness, equanimity, are the four great mental states.

92
00:08:48,219 --> 00:08:52,187
These we can develop indefinitely, right?

93
00:08:52,488 --> 00:08:57,394
And it's often translated as appreciative joy, reciprocal joy.

94
00:08:58,376 --> 00:09:02,582
And what this does, of course, is it undermines envy and jealousy.

95
00:09:03,063 --> 00:09:14,360
And I define those two as saying that envy is wanting what the other person has and jealousy is wanting what the other person has and hating them for having it in the first place.

96
00:09:16,011 --> 00:09:28,610
Now, it's interesting in the East, you know, if you make a donation to a cause, if you make a donation to a, say, a monastery, all the names are posted up with exactly how much you gave.

97
00:09:28,730 --> 00:09:35,299
You know, so it starts off with, I don't know, maybe a thousand pounds and it goes all the way down to, you know, a couple of shillings.

98
00:09:36,081 --> 00:09:37,243
That's an old word, isn't it?

99
00:09:37,595 --> 00:09:51,894
So if you, if you, and it's done because in the East, it's understood that people will rejoice in the good karma that you have gained by your offering.

100
00:09:54,337 --> 00:10:04,951
Now, when it came to Bill Gates giving his millions away, I wonder what our response was, you know, when he got all that money, he should be able to give something away, you know, the one percenters.

101
00:10:05,759 --> 00:10:09,984
Did we say, oh, good on Bill, you know, may he receive many blessings.

102
00:10:10,945 --> 00:10:12,285
He's got enough blessings.

103
00:10:15,089 --> 00:10:21,395
So here we have that reciprocal joy of actually being joyful in somebody else's successes and joys.

104
00:10:21,956 --> 00:10:28,384
And I think it comes as a revelation that we can actually be more joyful for others than for ourselves.

105
00:10:29,065 --> 00:10:35,412
And this is not strange, of course, to parents who rejoice in the successes of their offsprings.

106
00:10:35,898 --> 00:10:43,009
You know, I remember once I must have been about maybe 12 years old because my sister's 11 years younger than me.

107
00:10:43,769 --> 00:10:51,081
And I got back from school and I sat opposite my mother and she held Maria, you see, and encouraged her to walk towards me.

108
00:10:51,623 --> 00:10:53,985
And of course, when she did, I mean, it was joy.

109
00:10:54,025 --> 00:10:58,833
You know, it was wonderful to see this little this little toddler trying to make his way.

110
00:11:00,399 --> 00:11:11,437
So this development of being joyful for other people in the joys of other people and the successes of other people is really heartlifting.

111
00:11:13,760 --> 00:11:16,445
And joy is also a restorative.

112
00:11:16,625 --> 00:11:18,327
Somebody's called it restorative joy.

113
00:11:18,347 --> 00:11:20,772
So there you are down in the dumps, right?

114
00:11:22,085 --> 00:11:25,309
And you think to yourself, well, how can I lift my heart?

115
00:11:25,671 --> 00:11:28,414
How can I bring joy into my heart?

116
00:11:28,796 --> 00:11:33,342
Whatever level, it doesn't always have to be amazing, ecstatic joy.

117
00:11:33,423 --> 00:11:35,787
It's just feeling happy, generally happy.

118
00:11:36,629 --> 00:11:42,979
So that's when you meet up with a friend or you watch a good film and so on.

119
00:11:43,144 --> 00:11:48,350
In the monastic life, of course, the daily routine tends to be the same.

120
00:11:49,149 --> 00:11:56,557
I mean, even when there's a feast day, the only difference is you turn up for a better meal and then you go back and it's just the same.

121
00:11:57,256 --> 00:12:03,923
So it can be very, you know, it can move you towards a sense of apathy, a sense of laziness and all that.

122
00:12:04,783 --> 00:12:10,349
And it was then that I realized the amazing power of a long, mindful cup of tea.

123
00:12:11,929 --> 00:12:12,831
No doubt about it.

124
00:12:16,927 --> 00:12:38,480
So, I mean, if we just list all those things, you know, this is not an exhaustive list, but, you know, just the sensual joys that we get that lift the heart, relations of happiness, just the religious joys of, you know, feast days.

125
00:12:38,714 --> 00:12:44,080
Now, the ethical joys are really what the Buddha points to, right?

126
00:12:44,100 --> 00:12:48,845
So as far as he's concerned, virtue goodness equals happiness.

127
00:12:49,846 --> 00:12:55,451
And in chapter 20 of the Dhammapada, which is a lot of the verses are devoted to being happy.

128
00:12:56,732 --> 00:12:57,594
This is what he says.

129
00:12:58,575 --> 00:13:05,142
Oh, how happily we live without hate among those with hate among people who hate.

130
00:13:05,241 --> 00:13:07,083
We live without hate.

131
00:13:08,126 --> 00:13:16,649
Oh, so how happily we live without misery among those in misery, among people in misery.

132
00:13:17,071 --> 00:13:18,475
We live without misery.

133
00:13:19,214 --> 00:13:24,479
Oh, how happily we live without ambition among those with ambition.

134
00:13:25,240 --> 00:13:29,024
Among people with ambition, we live without ambition.

135
00:13:29,684 --> 00:13:31,907
Now, just a note on that ambition.

136
00:13:32,488 --> 00:13:40,576
There's nothing wrong with us offering our talents for the benefit of the company, people, et cetera, et cetera.

137
00:13:41,116 --> 00:13:46,081
But of course, it becomes corrupt when we start thinking about money and power.

138
00:13:48,543 --> 00:13:53,130
So the whole idea, really, if we want to develop joy, is to bend that way.

139
00:13:55,153 --> 00:13:55,875
So here it is.

140
00:13:55,916 --> 00:13:57,097
So what have we talked about?

141
00:13:57,138 --> 00:13:59,380
We've talked about the enemies of joy.

142
00:13:59,721 --> 00:14:11,461
We realize how corruptive indulgence is, how it becomes an obsession, how it's what they call it, feeding the dragon, you know.

143
00:14:11,999 --> 00:14:17,065
And because of that, we can't allow ourselves to enjoy something.

144
00:14:17,605 --> 00:14:21,490
And then, of course, there's the indulgence itself, which becomes a trap in itself.

145
00:14:21,530 --> 00:14:23,113
That's feeding the dragon.

146
00:14:24,875 --> 00:14:33,264
And the way we do it is by becoming more aware of our daily joys and just bending life towards that way, just as we do with metta.

147
00:14:34,020 --> 00:14:42,292
Then we have this reciprocal joy, you know, undermining envy and jealousy and really being happy for other people's happiness.

148
00:14:43,273 --> 00:14:48,219
And finally, to use joy to lift the heart when we feel a bit down in the dumps.

149
00:14:48,539 --> 00:14:48,799
Yeah.

150
00:14:50,501 --> 00:14:52,585
So here are some exercises.

151
00:14:55,107 --> 00:14:56,850
You have to make a resolution, you see.

152
00:14:56,910 --> 00:15:00,315
If at the end of today you sit and you think now,

153
00:15:00,952 --> 00:15:03,015
You know, how happy was I today?

154
00:15:03,115 --> 00:15:05,600
And all you can remember is the miseries.

155
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:13,693
Then you have to make a determination that tomorrow you'll actually acknowledge when you're happy, any level of happiness, any level of joy.

156
00:15:13,714 --> 00:15:14,916
I could just be contentment.

157
00:15:15,537 --> 00:15:15,677
Right.

158
00:15:15,736 --> 00:15:20,784
And just to acknowledge it and doing that, of course, you remember it by the end of the day.

159
00:15:22,283 --> 00:15:34,871
The other thing you might try to do is to contemplate every evening for about a week, maybe five, 10 minutes, and just go back in your life and just think of all the joys you've had.

160
00:15:35,113 --> 00:15:36,836
Yeah, all the joys you've had.

161
00:15:37,357 --> 00:15:40,865
And by the end of the week, you'll have a big smile on your face.

162
00:15:42,652 --> 00:15:46,164
And the other thing is the practice of joy, which is like meta.

163
00:15:46,345 --> 00:15:53,893
So you go through all the categories, but the blessings are, may you be joyful, may you be ever more joyful.

164
00:15:54,261 --> 00:15:58,269
Now, those are the, shall we say, the ones that are regularly used.

165
00:15:58,831 --> 00:16:04,562
I like to add, may you attain the sublime peace of Nibbana.

166
00:16:04,581 --> 00:16:09,572
Now, the problem with Nibbana is that there's no emotions in Nibbana, right?

167
00:16:10,312 --> 00:16:12,878
So it's not that sort of happiness.

168
00:16:13,414 --> 00:16:15,437
In fact, that's what Sariputta said.

169
00:16:15,457 --> 00:16:19,625
He says it's the very absence of emotions, which is the bliss of Nibbana.

170
00:16:20,085 --> 00:16:28,818
That's a bit difficult for us, but at least we can, shall we say, make that intention because, you know, according to the Buddha, this is the highest of all happinesses.

171
00:16:29,980 --> 00:16:31,403
So may you be joyful.

172
00:16:31,803 --> 00:16:33,886
May you be ever more joyful.

173
00:16:34,035 --> 00:16:37,039
May you attain the sublime peace of Nibbana.

174
00:16:37,059 --> 00:16:38,562
So I think peace rather than bliss.

175
00:16:38,621 --> 00:16:40,063
I've sometimes used bliss.

176
00:16:41,206 --> 00:16:44,750
You know, peace gives you, I think, a slightly better feel for it.

177
00:16:48,855 --> 00:16:54,744
And as I say, at the end of this hour, that's what I'll be doing.

178
00:16:54,803 --> 00:16:58,609
I'll be doing joyful meditation instead of metta.

179
00:17:01,475 --> 00:17:02,297
Very good.

180
00:17:02,657 --> 00:17:15,281
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that I have not caused confusion, and that by your development of joy, you will be joyful sooner rather than later.

